           SPELL=chrony
         VERSION=1.19-pre2
        #VERSION=1.18 #for stable
          SOURCE=$SPELL-$VERSION.tar.gz
SOURCE_DIRECTORY=$BUILD_DIRECTORY/$SPELL-$VERSION
#Attempting to download from the ftp site results in getting a symlink.
   #SOURCE_URL[0]=ftp://chrony.sunsite.dk/projects/chrony/$SOURCE
   SOURCE_URL[1]=http://chrony.sunsite.dk/download/$SOURCE
   #SOURCE_URL[2]=ftp://metalab.unc.edu/pub/Linux/system/admin/time/$SOURCE
   SOURCE_URL[3]=http://www.ibiblio.org/pub/Linux/system/admin/time/$SOURCE
          MD5[0]=aa6395167329310a53ed7aecbdbdc221 #1.19-pre2
         #MD5[0]=d593763a87288eafe327015453bc9b1d #1.18
        WEB_SITE=http://chrony.sunsite.dk/
         ENTERED=20021216
         UPDATED=20021216
      LICENSE[0]=GPL
           SHORT="chrony syncs your time with an ntp server"
cat << EOF
Chrony is an implementation of Network Time Protocol by Richard Curnow.
It handles an intermittently connected computer better than the ntp program,
but does not yet know how to use a hardware reference clock (GPS receiver,
cesium clock, etc.)

It has two programs: chronyd, the daemon, which talks on UDP port 123 to
other time servers, and chronyc, which asks chronyd on port 323 how well
it's keeping time.
EOF
